    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become connected in such a way that their properties, like spin or momentum, are correlated regardless of the distance between them. This means that measuring the state of one particle instantly affects the state of the other entangled particles, even if they're separated by vast distances. In contrast, classical correlation refers to the predictable and simultaneous behavior of two or more variables, but it doesn't involve the instantaneous and non-local effects seen in entanglement. Think of entanglement as a \"quantum connection\" that transcends space and time, whereas classical correlation is just a statistical relationship.",
      "source": "target",
