    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. but i keep seeing people call it \"spooky action at a distance.\" why do they use that word? is there something actually weird or \"spooky\" about how the particles interact?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The phrase \"spooky action at a distance\" was coined by Albert Einstein, who was skeptical of entanglement at first. He felt that the instantaneous correlation between entangled particles was \"spooky\" because it seemed to defy classical notions of space and time. Einstein's concerns were rooted in the idea that information couldn't travel faster than the speed of light, but entanglement appears to allow for instantaneous communication between particles, regardless of distance. The name stuck, though, and now \"spooky action at a distance\" is widely used to describe this peculiar phenomenon.",
      "source": "target",
